76561198039309460,Not Recommended,271760,20341723,"Posted: 5 January, 2016",all,Bingis,"This review is mainly for people who played the original game back in 200X.I played this game back in the day when it was chock full of bugs, empty towns, characters that were void of any interest and a multiplayer system that would cause the game to crash...And you know what? I loved it.For some reason there was a charm to the way that the game allowed you to stand there, shooting your bow for 20+ minutes to kill enemies that were never meant to be fought at your level, finally killing them and gaining hundreds of thousands of experience points. The game also rewarded you for playing on harder difficulties by rewarding more experience.I remember doing backflips in full plate armour over mountains to reach areas that were meant for the final hours of the game. The way I was able to increase my speed so my jump attacks would shred the enemies like a wood chipper was also hilarious.The game's mechanics made it fun, giving you the ability to use whatever spells you find as long as you had the proper ingredients, equip whatever weapons and armour you wanted with penalties if you didn't have the required stats and of course the magical power to pause the game in any menu and wait for your stuns and debuffs to wear off while the myriad of enemies politely wait for you to check your stats or find that spellbook that you really need.If I were to give it an honest rating, it'd likely be a 3/10. It wasn't a good game at all, though it was fun and hilarious despite all these shortcomings. I would compare it to movies like ""The Room"" or ""Spiderman 3"", as I don't think either of these movies are good, though they're hilarious fun.Now to describe my experience with the steam edition. The cool starting menu was taken out, which made me frown, though I can get past that. My character was a Zaur fighter, much like my previous playthroughs which eventually became deathlords by the end of the game. They give you starting rune spells which I found kind of strange, though they were useful. As I killed my first few groups of goblins, I noticed that I couldn't equip bows. ""But... But why, though"", I asked. Later I realized that the only spells I WAS allowed to use were the ones given to me by leveling up, making it seem like a bad singleplayer version of a tab-targetting MMORPG. When I finally got to a shopkeeper, I sold all my junk weapons and armour, ending up with over 10k gold (which for some reason is noted with a $ sign). I was able to buy everything I needed at any point because nothing costed enough to make a dent in my wallet. I remember in the old game there was a weapon called the giant battle axe, which required 35 strength to use without penalty. I ended up chopping through enemies like they were made of chocolate with it, despite my strength score of 20. The point at which I was no longer able to handle the changes was when I arrived at the council of ancient elders. You see, in the original game, you could stand there hacking away for minutes on end and take out these huge health boss ghosts and get loads of exp. Now they're level 80 and I can only hit them once every few minutes...In short, the core game is still there. The issue is that the core game was the worst part of it and they changed all the charming bits of it that I liked. If you actually enjoyed the story and were annoyed by the bugs and glitches, this is for you. If you enjoyed the old game because of how stupid it was in spite of its serious tone, I'd recommend staying away from this one.""I MEAN YOU NO HARM!""- Messenger Simon, 2005"
76561197979875832,Recommended,271760,20248096,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,Prustan,"On the whole, I did enjoy it.  The graphics have been updated somewhat so they don't look horrible, and the inventory system has been overhauled somewhat to make it clear how much stuff you can haul around before needing to get rid of something.Unfortunately, trying to sell multiples of something to a vendor means needing to close the inventory screen to select how much you're selling, then reopening it to sell the next item.  Also, the change to the class/skills means that alot of the freedom of the original game has been lost, as you are no longer free to spend your experience to increase your skills and attributes as you wish, instead having a much more limited pool of attribute and skill points gained each level.  And, you no longer have 2 Basic, 2 Advanced, and 1 Master class, but 2 Basic, 1 Advanced, and 1 Master, decreasing your options even more.Still, it's a decent enough RPG, especially if you can pick it up during a sale."
,Recommended,271760,31264004,Posted: 20 April,all,Aythadis,"I own an older version of this game.http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=902854473Though as it's been YEARS since I last played it, I don't remember a whole lot of it. I just know it was an OK game. Not the worst, but not the greatest either. Hell I didn't even know they made a Steam version! I only noticed it when a friend recently bought it when it was -75% off. So I grabbed it as well, sat down one night and just played through it.Playing the old version, there was some problems. Graphically it was average, and could barely keep up to 20FPS, the draw distance wasn't that far, the controls were a little clunky, and the difficulty was insanely brutal if you weren't playing a Tank build, at least for me. Back then I think I ended up making 4 different characters, and the only one that was able to not die was my tank. Playing anything but made the game really difficult. Compared to the old version, this version is alright. This game runs at a smooth 60FPS, the graphics are polished up a little bit, they added/fixed some of the control problems, cleaned up/improved the UI, fixed the difficulty, etc.Though this game still has some problems. The major one is when you are in game, there is no possible way to view the ""options"" menu. You have to quit to the main menu to be able to change anything. There isn't even a pause option in this game. When you open up your menu's or even the save/load screen, the game does not pause. This is annoying for a reason which I will explain.This game has a ""random encounter"" feature to it, where almost anywhere you are (other than certain buildings/stores) there may be a random encounter... or in other words an enemy or group of enemies that want to kill you. This can range from a thief, to a swarm of bats, or a horde of goblins. This is even possible in the middle of town! Combine this with no pause menu, you can be looking through your inventory to sort your bags or add your stats from your level up, and you can be jumped. In this version the chance of having an encounter is really high. There is an option to set how often this happens, but as stated you can't do that in game.Another issue, partly from how the game was built, is that when you are in big areas (not in caves/dungeons/towns) you will experience ""mini loadings"" here and there. This tends to get annoying when you are running down a path, then suddenly stop for a ""loading"" for a few seconds, then continue on for about a min before you are hit with another ""loading"". Again this is partially on how the game was originally built, and don't think it would be possible to remove it.Now, this is probably the biggest fault of the game, but the map design/world design, is just horrible at times. The first few hours of this game is by far the worst thing about this game. There is no store in the beginning for you to unload your junk, and is impossible to go back to the first area after you leave. It takes a few hours to get into town, and it's a rough ride as well. You will be fighting big groups of goblins, and have WAY more loot than you can ever carry, so you have to leave most of it behind. On top of that, in order to even be able to get out, you will be fighting a strong Ogre boss. In my playthrough, I was only level 6, and the Ogre boss was level 12. The game can be cheap, so be warned. Even after you get to town, good luck finding the stores/guilds as there is no navigation or sign posts telling you what is where, and no NPC's will tell you either. You will get lost in the town.Like I said, it's not the worst, but not the greatest either. But it IS fun to play through. I didn't really want to play through it again (as there is no achievements, so I don't really wanna waste too much time on it again) as I just replaying it just for fun and Nostalgia sake. Growing up poor and not really able to go and buy new games all the time, so you had to bargain bin shop, this is one of those games. For the many flaws, it's still a fun adventure to play through this old 2005 game.Just like the old version, there is 8 player coop... But apperently it doesn't work well, as it's direct connection to the host. I never tried it out, but then I never played online for this game originally.Pros:- Runs smooth- Old school RPG with some interesting ideas- Fun to play- Improved difficulty- Steam Traiding CardsCons:- Little pricey- The game takes 3 steps forward, then 1 step back compared to older versions- Poor level design- Story is average- Difficulty/Random Encounters are still a pain- Mini ""Loading"" in large areas.- Controls/camera can be clunky at times- Multiplayer net code is old/doesn't work well- No AchievementsFor $15 it's a little pricey, especially for an older game that didn't do well like this. If you are interested, wait till it hits -75% or more."
